5. Changes to be Implemented

After analyzing these 33 data points, the following changes are recommended for
the next development phase:
Frontend UI Cleanup: Cut Navbar vertical padding in half and implement a
sticky header.
Back-end Database Design Changes: Include a status flag on orders to indicate
delivery/collection status.
User Interface Redesign: Use an <input> instead of "dropdown-content" on the CSS
Grid system to create product cards.
Accessibility Audit: Move away from a strong green color scheme (for instance,
#2d5a27) as it hinders text legibility.



This analysis reveals an important discrepancy between the theoretical and practical
usability of the site. While technically everything is impeccable – the database is secure,
calculations are correct, and logical connections make perfect sense – as soon as actual
users began to navigate the site, it turned out that the ability of a site to work perfectly well
is not always equal to its ability to satisfy users.
Among other problems, it can be noted that there were some serious concerns about the
navigation bar. Both Stanley, Josh, and Evie-Mae considered the navigation bar too
distracting and too large. With such a big header, the page becomes almost a barricade that
prevents the user from seeing the products he or she wants to examine. In fact, people come
to buy something and not admire the logo, so it makes sense to shrink the bar and make it
sticky.
Another important lesson learned from the feedback was provided by Danil regarding the
dropdown menus. Selecting goods with the use of a drop-down is like reading a menu from
a restaurant through a keyhole – you are seeing one item at a time. However, shopping is
visual, which means that switching to a CSS Grid will transform the website into a vibrant
online farmers&#39; market.
However, not everything was about criticisms – the inner workings of the project received a
perfect grade. As noticed by Evie-Mae, there is no difference between the columns of the
database and the PHP files – they use the same terminology which ensures that the
programming is neat, professional, and easily manageable. Regardless if it is a £2.50
delivery fee or logic behind collecting loyalty points – the mind of the website does not
make mistakes.
Last but not least, the advice regarding the bright green color served as a wake-up call.
When using too intense of a background color, white font tends to tremble and fade. Thus,
for elderly visitors and those with eye problems, the website may become impossible to
read. Switching to more natural Forest Green color will definitely improve this problem.
